===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|brewen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|brēowan}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*brewwaną}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*bʰreuh₁-}}, {{term/t|ine-pro|*bʰreh₁u-}} (compare Welsh {{term|berw||boiling|lang=cy}}, Latin {{term/t|la|fervēre}}, Albanian {{term|mbruaj||to knead|lang=sq}}, Russian {{term|бруя||current|tr=brujá|lang=ru}}, Sanskrit {{term|भुर्वन्||motion of water|tr=bhurván|lang=sa}}).

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|bro͞o}}, {{IPA|/bruː/}}
* {{rhymes|uː}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[prepare]] (usually a [[beverage]]) by [[steep]]ing and [[mingle|mingling]]; to [[concoct]].
#* [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]]
#*: Go, '''brew''' me a pottle of sack finely.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[foment]] or prepare, as by brewing; to [[contrive]]; to [[plot]]; to hatch.
#* [[w:John Milton|John Milton]]
#*: Hence with thy '''brewed''' enchantments, foul deceiver!
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To [[attend]] to the business, or go through the processes, of brewing or making beer.
#* [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]]
#*: I wash, wring, '''brew''', bake, scour.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To be in a state of preparation; to be [[mix]]ing, forming, or [[gather]]ing.
#* [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]]
#*: There is some ill a-'''brewing''' towards my rest.
#* {{quote-news
